<HEAD>3-Year-Old Can Recite Greek Alphabet, Read At Second-Grade Level</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troy and Trina Kinast have to watch what
they say around their 3-year-old son.
   Seth Kinast, according to his parents, can already recite the
Greek alphabet, say the English alphabet forward and backward,
count in Spanish, German and English, read at a second-grade level,
identify countries on a globe, recite the books of the New
Testament and keep up with adult conversations.
   Seth began saying ``Mommy'' and ``Daddy'' at about 8 months. At
16 months, he named the letters of the alphabet. At 22 months, he
read magazine headlines at a grocery store, the Kinasts said.
   The couple read books to the unborn child because they heard it
could stimulate letter and sound recognition. After Seth was born,
they read or sang to him as they rocked him to sleep.
   ``Now we read to him before naps and bedtime,'' Kinast said.
``He has a stack of books by his bed, and he reads to himself.
Sometimes at 11:30 p.m., we have to tell him to quit, but he always
says, `Just one more.'''
   More than 800 books line the shelves in Seth's bedroom.
   Recently, Seth and his grandmother were getting ready to play
``Sorry!'' when his grandmother realized she didn't have her
glasses. Seth read her the rules from the game box, Kinast said.
   The Kinasts already have decided to teach Seth at home and
provide lessons in piano and organ. And they're beginning to teach
younger brother Nathan, 8 months old. Kinast is a math instructor
at Wichita State University; Mrs. Kinast stays home with the
children.
   He said he and his wife are not overdrilling Seth or forcing him
to learn things against his will.
   ``It's like a game,'' he said. ``He learned the ABC song, and
then we learned the letters backward by putting them to the song.
... When we doodle, we doodle shapes, letters and designs. When we
play hide and seek, we count in German.''
</TEXT>
