<HEAD>Unusual 3-Year-Old Kansas Boy's Abilities Attracting Wide Interest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been a whirlwind of activity for
Troy and Trina Kinast and their son Seth since people started
hearing about what the 3-year-old boy can do.
   Since last week, Seth has been in newspaper headlines and he's
been sought-after for network talk shows. Appearances are scheduled
with syndicated talk-show hosts David Letterman and Sally Jesse
Raphael.
   Seth is in demand because of his amazing ability to learn.
   He can count in three languages, recite the English alphabet
forward and backward and read at an upper second-grade level. His
parents say he has already mastered the Greek alphabet.
   ``We are just overwhelmed,'' Mrs. Kinast said of the numerous
telephone calls requesting interviews with her son.
   ``I feel like I am in a fog,'' said Kinast, just back a trip to
New York on Tuesday and Wednesday for an appearance on CBS' ``This
Morning.'' ``I don't think I have awakened yet.''
   The family was returning to New York for an appearance on the
David Letterman show on NBC on Friday.
   He said Seth stared, mouth agape, at New York's skyline and
played in the large back seat of the limousine that took them to
the airport.
   ``It was crowded,'' Seth said Wednesday after arriving home from
New York. He described the limo as the ``longest.''
   Mrs. Kinast said she and her husband never thought of their son
as a genius.
   ``We just took our time with him,'' she said. ``He is just a
normal 3-year-old kid full of orneriness.''
   Her husband said that because he and his wife are first-time
parents, they had no one to compare to Seth and were surprised by
all the attention.
   ``We have friends that have children Seth's age, and we didn't
see a whole lot of difference,'' Kinast said. ``When 3-year-olds
converse, the Greek alphabet and the names of shapes don't come
into play.''
   Seth has access to nearly 1,000 books and ``the computer is his
toy,'' his father said.
   Learning has become like playing.
   ``This is an everyday thing for him,'' said his mother. ``It is
just fun and games. We don't have a television, and Seth has to
play an active role instead of a passive role.''
</TEXT>
