<HEAD>Child Slain After Unable To Recite Alphabet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-year-old died after his stepfather allegedly
beat him with a tree limb, a belt and his hands because the boy
couldn't recite the alphabet past ``G,'' authorities said.
   Dwayne Blocker, 24, was being held in the Cook County Jail today
on $150,000 bond, said a jailer who refused to give her name. He is
to be arraigned April 4.
   Blocker, who was indicted on murder charges by a county grand
jury Friday, admitted beating stepson Charles Moss because he could
only reach ``G'' when Blocked asked him to say the alphabet, said
police Lt. James Phelan.
   The boy's mother, Joyce Blocker, 21, was sick Wednesday and
Blocker picked up Charles from preschool, Phelan said.
   After the child could not complete the alphabet, Blocker
shouted, ``Do it again,'' the lieutenant said.
   ``Then he punched him several times, hit him with a belt several
times and then went outside and got a tree branch and struck him
several more times,'' Phelan said.
   After the attack, the boy ran upstairs to his mother's room,
said David Schneidman, a spokesman for the state Department of
Children and Family Services.
   Charles collapsed in the room, and the stepfather tried to
revive him, Schneidman said.
   The youngster, who died at St. Francis Cabrini Hospital, had a
broken arm, bruises on his leg and a solid bruise from the shoulder
blade to his buttocks, Schneidman said.
   ``When this guy said he became angry because the boy could not
get past the letter G, that sounds absurd, ridiculous,'' he said.
``But frankly, reasons like that are very common among child
abusers.
   ``In severe abuse cases, there are several things that can
trigger an incident,'' said Schneidman. ``The child's learning
ability is one of the common reasons. Others are eating habits and
toilet training.''
   Another child from the family, 1-year-old Jasmine Blocker, was
admitted to the hospital to check for potential abuse, Schneidman
said. The state has moved to gain temporary custody of her.
</TEXT>
