<HEAD>OK To Exclude W Through Z From Jury Pool, Court Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks, Hispanics and women can't be kept
off juries as a group, but it's OK to exclude people whose last
names begin with the letters W through Z.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled 3-0 Wednesday that
jurors at the end of alphabetical order do not constitute ``a
recognizable and distinct class'' covered by court decisions
barring discrimination in jury selection. The claim was raised by a
man whose last name begins with a W _ William Jefferson Walker.
   He was convicted of aggravated assault and leaving the scene of
an accident in Pima County, Ariz., in September 1983 and sentenced
to 10 years in prison. For reasons not explained by the court, the
pool from which the jury was chosen included no one with a surname
starting with W through Z.
   Walker cited a psychologist's study, published in 1970, that
concluded people whose names started with letters from S to Z were
50 percent more likely than others to develop a condition called
``alphabetic neurosis.''
   The court noted that two other appeals courts have rejected
similar claims, one of them involving a jury made up entirely of
people whose names began with the letters T through Z.
</TEXT>
