<DESCRIPT>  READING; EDUCATION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE ads are everywhere: Send away for Hooked on Phonics -- the "magical"
educational program set to music -- and learn to read.;   The sales pitch is a
smash hit. The cassette kits, at $179.95 a pop, are flying out of an Orange
County warehouse at the rate of 7,000 a week.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOOKED ON PHONICS SOUNDS GOOD, BUT DOES IT WORK?  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Education  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     With almost a half-million kits sold nationwide, Hooked on Phonics is one
of the hottest educational tools around. Its manufacturer, Gateway Educational
Products of Orange, says it is being snapped up about equally by adults with
reading problems and by parents of children having trouble learning to read at
school.;   It has clearly tapped into a huge market of people unsatisfied with
-- or unaware of -- the options available at schools and through literacy
programs.;   The debate over Hooked on Phonics, however, has become almost as
hot as its sales reports.;   Reading or rote-learning?; Supporters say that by
making learning fun, Hooked on Phonics makes reading more accessible to
everyone from young children to illiterate adults.;   Critics -- including
some of the nation's leading experts on reading -- argue that the
eight-cassette program doesn't live up to its billing. At best, they say,
Hooked on Phonics teaches only one aspect of reading -- the ability to sound
out words -- without teaching their meaning.;   What you get for your money:; 
 (check) Eight cassette tapes, with directions and drills set to a catchy and
rhythmic synthesized music background. An upbeat speaker leads users from
lessons on the alphabet, to lessons on the sounds letters make, to sounding
out words.;   (check) Nine sets of color-coded flashcards that go along with
the tapes. The first set is the letters of the alphabet. Other sets show
sounds letters make alone and when combined with other letters, and short
words.;   (check) Five workbooks, starting with simple words and ending with
full sentences.;   John Shanahan, president of Gateway and creator of the
program, said one of its greatest strengths is the music, which he said
stimulates the brain and makes the learning fun.;   Though Shanahan has little
statistical information to prove that Hooked on Phonics works, he does have
plenty of testimonials from adults and children who swear by the program.;   A
new, old-fashioned idea;   One satisfied user is Robert Pierce, 10, of Garden
Grove. Robert -- who appears in one of the product's commercials -- was far
behind his grade level in reading before he used Hooked on Phonics. Now he's
ahead.;   "When I started Hooked on Phonics, it wasn't easy," Robert said. But
eventually, he added, "I, like, started having fun.";   Robert said he liked
the music and liked using the flashcards. "I like reading now," he said.;  
Robert's father bought the program after hearing an ad on the radio. His
mother became such a fan she went to work for Gateway.;   Ironically, this new
program is being attacked because of its single-minded adherence to an old
strategy: phonics, the process of teaching the letters in the alphabet and the
sounds they make.;   Many experts now think phonics should be only one tool
used to teach reading. But Shanahan, 51, a boisterous Balboa resident and
former musician, said phonics is the only way to learn reading. He said the
greatest evidence of the success of the program is that its 30-day money-back
guarantee is used by fewer than 10 percent of his customers.;   When he
watches a 5-year-old on one of his promotional videotapes read sentences
haltingly from a book, Shanahan is delighted. And if the youngster doesn't
understand every word on the tape, Shanahan isn't bothered.;   "Is that
important at this point in his life?" he asked.;   Shanahan's critics,
however, would answer that it is. They say reading is much more than just
being able to sound out words -- it has to do with understanding the words.
The new guideline for teaching reading in California public schools, for
instance, stresses a "whole language" approach that emphasizes meaning over
sounds.;   Among the strongest critics of Hooked on Phonics is Jeanne Chall,
professor of education at Harvard University. In her report to the
International Reading Association, she criticized the kits for concentrating
solely on the sounds of letters rather than the meaning.;   Furthermore, she
said, there is no instruction given on how to blend the letter sounds once
they are learned.;   Literacy workers, too, have been critical, claiming the
free programs they offer illiterate adults are far superior to Hooked on
Phonics.;   Evelyn Renner, a field services director for Literacy Volunteers
of America in Anaheim, said the marketing raises false hopes. "The tapes are
being bought by adult readers who think they're going to learn to read in 18
minutes," she said.;   Shanahan, however, noted that literacy programs have
failed to reach millions of adults with reading problems who apparently find
their programs embarrassing or inconvenient, and want something they can use
at home.;   Julie Chan, a reading specialist with the Orange County Department
of Education, listened to the cassette program recently and came away with a
mixed review.;   Among the things Chan liked about Hooked on Phonics: the
repetition, the music, the narrator's voice and optimism and the incremental
nature of the program.;   But when Chan took the program home to be used by
her mother, who is literate in Chinese but not English, she found the
instructions frustrating.;   "If you can't get beyond the logistics, you can't
get started," Chan said.;   Chan said the program is better for some groups
than for others. Adult native-English-speaking illiterates would recognize
most of the words because they have large vocabularies. But children or
non-native speakers, who know the meanings of fewer words, could be left
clueless.;   Shanahan, however, insists the kit is great for everybody. "My
God," he said, "people need this."  </TEXT>
