<LEADPARA>  WHY DOES THE ALPHABET ON THE telephone start on the 2 digit rather than on the
1? And why aren't the letters Q and Z used?;   LONG AGO, THE PHONE SYSTEM WAS
REally primitive. How primitive was it? So primitive that, instead of buttons,
they had "dials." This was some kind of circular configuration with holes for
your fingers corresponding to the numbers. Hard to believe, but true.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  West  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THAT'S WHY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Anyway, when you dialed the 1, it sent out a pulse, a single clicking sound
(a 2 was two clicks, etc.). According to Chuck Starnes of Bell Laboratories in
Indianapolis, the fussy old switching equipment at the phone company could
easily get confused, and mistakenly think that a random clicking noise on the
line was someone trying to dial a number beginning with 1. Thus a rule was
made: No phone number can start with 1. This rule is still observed, though
solely for the sake of tradition -- you now dial 1 to get access to the long
distance network, and this doesn't cause any confusion for the modernized
equipment.;   Now for the alphabet. It's there to help you remember numbers.
This was particularly necessary in the old days, when phone books weren't as
common as they are now. People incorporated letters into their numbers, with
the letters often standing for a place name. Instead of 555-5000, the number
would be labelled KL-5-5000, which would be relayed orally as "Klondike five,
five thousand.";   Since phone numbers couldn't start with 1, Ma Bell didn't
want to put the ABC there. So the alphabet started with 2. Unfortunately, the
0 was reserved for "Oper," so there was space for only 24 letters, not 26.
They bumped the rarely used Q and the Z.;   The real question is, what should
we say now instead of "dialing the number"?;   Beeping the number?;   Stabbing
the number?;   The perfect word, unfortunately, is already taken:
"Prestidigitation."  </TEXT>
