<LEADPARA>  Greek has one of the longest written histories of any living language. Its
classical form still appeals to a few scholars as an object of study. Its New
Testament form may well attract more: divinity students, practicing ministers,
and the devout or just plain intellectually curious. GreekTools, from Parsons
Technology of Cedar Rapids, Iowa, brings it to the computer screen.;   
GreekTools has more than 1,150 entries -- words and characters that appear at
least 10 times in the Greek New Testament. They are organized like a stack of
index cards, and you can flip through them as you would flashcards, seeing the
word, its definition and other information. If you have something to add, you
can attach your own notes.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Computing  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE GREEKS INVADE THE COMPUTING AGE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Software  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The notes can be in English -- that is, the Roman alphabet -- or in either
Greek or Hebrew. Pressing one key changes the alphabet. It's something of a
shock to see Greek or Hebrew characters appear on the screen.;    Of course,
the three alphabets are not identical, but the programmers have done the best
they could. In Greek, for example, the "alpha" character appears when you
press "a," "beta" for "b." However, for "theta" the "q" key has to serve.;   
You can use GreekTools as a set of electronic flashcards, or you can construct
tests from them, edit them, add more to increase the vocabulary and tag sets
of words to concentrate on or to print out to study away from the computer.
The printer, by the way, must be compatible with Epson dot-matrix or H-P
LaserJet machines to produce the Greek or Hebrew alphabets.;    There is also
a terse summary of the grammatical material covered in two years of
college-level Greek, a catalog of manuscripts, information on textual
criticism that should have been better proofread, and a stripped-down word
processor for making notes.;    The manual is clear, and an accompanying book,
"Learn New Testament Greek," by John H. Dobson, helps those for whom
GreekTools is the first exposure to the language.;    The program requires a
computer with at least 512 kilobytes of working memory and MS-DOS 2.11 or
later. It comes on either 5 1/4-inch or 3 1/2-inch disks and may be installed
on a hard disk. Its retail price is $49 and it may be ordered by calling (800)
