<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Sun Ra says he came from Saturn. When you can play like he can,
why not?  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; PROFILE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  LET'S get this out of the way first: Sun Ra is a genius. Eccentric,
definitely. But an innovator nonetheless.;   In the years to come, this
septuagenarian pianist, poet and orchestrator -- who says he hails from Saturn
-- will be spoken of and praised in the same terms now used for the late Miles
Davis. They will say he was ahead of his time and regret they couldn't catch
up to him during his lifetime.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE SUN GOD
SUN RA BELIEVES IN ALIENS, DIVINE DEEP-SPACE
MESSAGES, TRICKY BACKWARD ALPHABETS
AND PURE, OTHERWORLDLY JAZZ  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     In the non-linear jazz world, his piano speaks a language that makes
perfect sense. He has found a way to get a 20-person band to improvise,
something thought to be accomplished only by small combos.;   In the world
that most of us inhabit, however, the Ra falls into that group of people who
walk the border close to madness.;   Some of his recent thoughts:;   "I played
in Turkey and Russia recently and they told me they've been talking to people
from outer space in ships circling the earth. They shared a cure for cancer. .
. .;   "There is a lot of space in outer space. You hear a lot of big bangs
there. If you hear one, that is God creating a new universe. If you hear it
you end up in a dimension you hadn't prepared for.";   Sort of like trying to
have a serious interview with the Ra.;   There have been times he's started
concerts with monologues on his thoughts of Egypt, flying saucers and sun
gods.;   In an interview last week, he talked about how Jesus was crucified.
People should say he was executed, the Ra says. It represents a beginning,
like when a musician executes with his horn.;   He also says the alphabet was
tinkered with somewhere along the line -- the letter A was really meant to be
a Z. This would change the meaning of a lot of words, he says, such as the
word "create," which is really supposed to be "crezte," like crest, a shield.
The missing letters change the whole meaning of the Bible, he says.;   I know
what you're thinking. Either he reads too many National Enquirers or this is a
publicity stunt. But I don't think so. He's been at it for 20 years longer
than Alice Cooper has used a girl's name.;   The Sun Ra also rises;   Back in
the '50s, according to several music encyclopedias, a musician named Herman
"Sonny" Blount left his role as a backup to jazz innovator Fletcher Henderson.
In his place stood Sun Ra, master of the cosmos.;   The books are sketchy on
this because Sun Ra is sketchy. All he says is that he came here from space,
in part to find people to play Henderson's music.;   Nearing 80, he's achieved
the status of an Indian medicine man or shaman with many fans. But not many
outside jazz circles have taken the time to hear his music.;   "That's because
I'm dealing with space and spirits and people weren't ready," he says. "I'm
still saying the same things I was years ago about going to Saturn, Mars and
Jupiter. It's very timely now.";   So what if he says ships can be powered
with cassettes of the right kind of music instead of rocket fuel?;   He says
it all clearly, softly, straightforwardly. He sounds -- almost -- like he
could be a bureaucrat or a school teacher.;   He has established a commune of
musicians in Philadelphia, requiring some of his backups to live with him,
drug- and alcohol-free. He told an interviewer in Philadelphia last year why
he moved there in 1969:;   "To save the planet, I had to go to the worst spot
on Earth, and that was Philadelphia, which is death's headquarters.";   He
regularly travels with a band of around 25 players. This year, he has been in
Europe and on the East Coast and will do a short swing through the Northwest.;
  One of the Ra's longtime backup musicians received the highest praise from
John Coltrane, one of jazz's top innovators, who credited John Gilmore as one
of his main influences.;   The lanky saxophonist could have had a huge career
on his own, but he has been playing with the Ra since 1963. Other great
players -- Marshall Allen and singer June Tyson -- also have tagged along.;  
Last year Sun Ra said he has asked Gilmore to save some of his most visionary
notes for some species better prepared to hear it.;   Close encounters of the
Ra kind;   In concert, the Ra is a time traveler. He entertains audiences with
primitive music, starting the band with conch shells and drums and then taking
them through the seven decades of jazz he has seen. Shows often end with a Sun
Ra vision of the future.;   His last two Bay Area tours have been a little
more down-to-earth. He played music from Walt Disney movies on one tour and
another featured classics by Duke Ellington and Fats Waller.;   This time,
he'll bring the synthesizer and do more spacey stuff.;   Although a stroke set
him back a year ago, Ra says he is feeling better now. Other band members say
he appears trimmer and fitter than he has in a while.;   "I'm always changing
improvisations," he says. "The world is changing and their thoughts about
space are changing. There is more talk about the possibility of going to outer
space, more magnification about things about space."; Sun Ra and His
Intergalactic Arkestra; When: Tonight-Sunday; Where: Koncepts Cultural
Gallery, 480 Third St., Oakland; Details: (510) 763-0682  </TEXT>
