<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Frenchman killed aboard a Greek cruise
ship during an attack by gunmen was himself a terrorist, the Greek
government said, but people who knew him denied the allegation.
   Sources also said an Arab passenger was arrested for possible
involvement in the bloody assault on stunned passengers sunbathing
on the City of Poros cruise ship.
   Nine people were killed and 98 were wounded in Monday's attack
when men fired automatic weapons and hurled hand grenades at
tourists when the ship was about 16 miles off the Greek coast in
the Aegean Sea.
   Police sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Friday
that an Arab man was being interrogated at police headquarters in
central Athens about possible involvement in the attack. They
declined to give details.
   Claims of responsibility have been attributed to three groups,
but none of the claims could be authenticated.
   One claim came in a letter purportedly sent by the Jewish
Defense League to the Greek Embassy in the Netherlands, the
state-run Athens News Agency reported today.
   The letter claims the Jewish extremist group staged the massacre
to protest Greece's support of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, the agency said. Leaders of the group could not
immediately be reached for comment.
   In Lebanon on Wednesday, a previously unknown group calling
itself the Organization of the Martyrs of the Popular Revolution in
Palestine claimed responsbility.
   Earlier, the Islamic Jihad organization purportedly claimed
responsbility in a telephone call to a French radio station from
Cairo.
   The Greek government statement identified the slain Frenchman as
Roland Vigneron, 23, and said he was involved in the attack.
   The statement also said the government had not ruled out that
another man identified as a terrorist, Mohammed Zozad, was among
the dead.
   It said police confirmed that the massacre was linked to a car
bomb explosion that killed two men near the ship's home dock about
six hours before the attack. The two were in the car when the bomb
apparently went off by mistake.
   ``Both actions were carried out by the same terrorist group,''
the statement said.
   The government statement said eight witnesses identified
Vigneron as one of the terrorists. It said he died of injuries at
Tzanneion Hospital in Piraeus, a port near Athens, where the
injured were rushed after the attack.
   In Paris, French television said a Frenchman named Laurent
Vigneron died in the attack.
   Greek authorities spell foreign names phonetically in Greek
script because they are unfamiliar with the Latin alphabet. They
apparently confused Roland with Laurent.
   Laurent Vigneron's parents confirmed he died of wounds at
Tzanneion Hospital.
   Reached by telephone in Mehun-sur-Yevre in central France,
Christine Audejean, the mother of Laurent Vigneron's girlfriend,
said she could not believe he was a terrorist. She said her
daughter, Annie, accompanied Vigneron on the cruise and is now
missing.
   ``We've known Laurent for two years. He's a very sweet boy, very
calm. They were lovers leaving on a honeymoon. They were going to
get engaged the following week,'' she said.
   She said both were engineering students in France.
   Mrs. Audejean said Vigneron was probably mistaken for a
terrorist because he had dark hair and complexion.
   The French Foreign Ministry said Friday it was not aware of any
evidence of Vigneron's involvement and asked Greek authorities to
provide an explanation.
   Police speculated that guns, grenades and explosives inside the
car that exploded were intended for hijacking the ship. They said
the terrorists may have been seeking freedom for Mohammed Rashid, a
Palestinian jailed in Greece for entering the country with a forged
Syrian passport.
   Rashid is wanted in the United States on murder charges and is
accused of planting a bomb on a Pan Am jumbo jet in 1982 that
killed one person and injured 15.
   The City of Poros was on a one-day trip through the Saronic Gulf
when terrorists struck.
   Initial accounts said the attackers fled in a waiting speedboat.
Later the gunmen were said to have jumped overboard and then
rescued with other passengers.
