<LEADPARA>  ARE we there yet?;    If you're anticipating a long summer car trip and
dreading Kid Travel Policy No. 1 (Spare No Whine Before Arrival Time), maybe
those wonderful specialty back-seat toys look irresistible.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BACK-SEAT WHINERS: KEEPING KIDS HAPPY WHEN
YOU'RE ON THE ROAD  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     We bet, though, one reason you're driving and not flying is money. At $120
for a Game Boy with video cartridge and $30 for a toddler's safari bag, the
distractions can defeat the purpose. So, what to do?;    Do as Pooh would do:
Think, think, think.;    There are toys that cost little and activities that
cost nothing, which together can make miles fly by. The key is planning.;   
The Parenting Guidance Center in Fort Worth, Texas, has a volunteer advisory
board of parents who put together some fundamentals that come with
experience.;    First, pack some toys that your child uses at no other time,
so they will hold some newness and fascination.;    For crowd control, an
adult should be in charge of the toy bag to ensure even distribution and avoid
an unmanageable mess. Bring along a kitchen timer to prevent back-seat brawls
over who had which toy for how long.;    Put small surprises -- a book, a
puzzle, a small game, a knickknack -- in little brown lunch bags, and use them
to count the distance, for example: one surprise every hour, or a surprise
when we get to Tucson.;    Involve your children in the ride by letting them
chart the journey or read about the region you're passing through. Rand
McNally now publishes the "Kid's U.S. Road Atlas" for $4, and also offers
separate $3 maps for Texas, California and Florida.;    Clap to the quacking; 
Come up with new variations on old standbys -- fresh verses for "Row, Row, Row
Your Boat" or barnyard solos for Beethoven's "Ode to Joy" (as in quack, moo,
woof.);    Have a period of storytelling -- an adult can lead the way for the
very young, and older kids can make up part and then hand off the tale.;   
Consider the classic road challenges: license plate bingo (you can buy cards)
or the "I'm thinking of a . . ." riddle game, in which a designated spotter
alludes to visible clues and spotters compete to guess first what the item
is.;    Using your ABCs;  And of course, alphabet, in which you each race
through the alphabet by spotting road sign or billboard words that begin with
the letter that comes next.;    Small personal stereos are ideal. And don't
pack only music; old radio shows, talking books and, for small children,
read-along tape-and-book sets offer variety.;    Stop regularly, change the
seating arrangement, include picnic stops that allow for exercise.;    And now
is prime time to buy downsized toys.;    Aggravation; Win, Lose or Draw; Wheel
of Fortune; Battleship; Connect Four; Hangman; and Yatzee are among the dozens
that come in travel sizes for $8 or less.;    If you want to make the trip
truly educational, consider the maps or a trip to the library for books.;   
Say your child is video-dependent? Consider under-$20 handheld electronic
games of the Double Dragon and Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtle variety.;    And
don't forget the change of clothing and wipes for spills, crackers for
unsettled tummies, raisins and juice for snacks.  </TEXT>
