<DESCRIPT>  ETHNIC; LEADER; REVIEW; ALAMEDA; COUNTY; ELECTION; CHANGE; PLANNING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Alameda County's alphabet soup attempts at redrawing supervisors' boundaries
have become as jumbled as, well, alphabet soup.;    The most recent maps
released last week -- dubbed P and Q -- were aimed at answering complaints
that an earlier plan -- named O -- split ethnically diverse East Oakland into
two districts.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ETHNIC LEADERS GIVE SUPERVISOR MAPS MIXED
REVIEWS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News Staff Writer Dennis Akizuki contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But the new-generation plans have drawn mixed reviews from leaders in the
black, Asian and Hispanic communities.;    Some like P. Some like Q. Some like
neither.;    And Fremont and Hayward are steaming over the way both maps -- as
well as many of their predecessors -- divide those two cities.;    At its
Tuesday night meeting, Fremont's city council authorized Mayor Bill Ball to
write a letter to the county expressing support for Plan K -- one that puts
Fremont, Newark and Union City into a single district.;    Facing harsh
criticism last month that said they were rushing to approve a plan,
supervisors postponed voting on the entire reapportionment issue until
Tuesday's meeting.;    Now it remains uncertain whether an agreement will be
reached by then.;    Community activists hope a vote is again delayed, noting
that, by law, the county has until November to set new boundaries.;    "We're
not wedded to an alphabet," said Sandre Swanson, a congressional aide who has
overseen the drawing of the latest maps. "We may end up with Z.";    Board
President Mary King of Oakland said last week she doubted she would be ready
to vote by Tuesday.;    "There's no unanimity on any of these plans," she
said. "I think there are some major flaws with each of the plans.";    Sandra
Soto, an aide to Supervisor Bill Aragon of Hayward, said her newly appointed
boss has just started meeting with constituents to solicit opinions.;   
"We've got maps. It's like wallpaper here," she said. "I can't say if he's got
a preference.";    Supervisor Ed Campbell of Fremont said he is waiting to see
which plans the other four supervisors select.;    "There's a good possibility
I could be a swing vote on this thing," said Campbell, adding that his goals
are to keep cities and ethnic voting blocs in the same districts.;    Last
month Supervisor Don Perata pro posed Plan O. But after lengthy discussions
with residents, Perata said he is committed to keeping East Oakland in one
district.;    But he hasn't decided which plan to support.;    "Somebody is
not going to be happy, that much I'm sure about," he said. "Some city is going
to get split.";    Supervisor Warren Widener of Berkeley couldn't be reached
for comment.;    "Since November is the deadline, I think another month
wouldn't hurt," Swanson said.;    Swanson, a former supervisorial candidate
and an aide to Rep. Ron Dellums of Oakland, led last month's attack on the
supervisors for hastily endorsing Plan O -- a map that divided several
southern Alameda County cities along with East Oakland.;    Since then,
Swanson, who is black, and other ethnic community leaders have met with
Perata, King and Widener to draw new maps to address complaints that East
Oakland's minority vote would be diluted.;    "What's healthy about this
process is that the board has been responsive," Swanson said. "They've opened
the issue back up.";    But in so doing, they've also created new divisions.; 
  Plan P, which keeps most of East Oakland in Perata's Third District, has the
support of many Asians, said Alan Yee, a director of the Organization of
Chinese Americans.;    Plan Q, which puts most of East Oakland into King's
Fourth District, has the support of many blacks, said Dezie Woods-Jones, a
member of the African American Coalition.;    And neither plan has the support
of the Latino Coalition of Alameda County, said member Teresa Limon.;    "I
don't know how (the supervisors are) going to deal with it," she said. "I wish
they would have just stayed with O.";    On Tuesday, members of the Hispanic
group plan to ask supervisors to delay a vote so the ethnic groups can try
once again to come up with a plan all can agree on, Limon said.;    "We're
still working on it," she said. "The three coalitions want to work together."  </TEXT>
