   TRAINING WHEELS. Nostalgia on the track.
   - The favorite toy of many a long-gone youth was the model
train. Lionel is featuring nostalgia in its 90th year by
reintroducing the Scale Hudson locomotive, which it first marketed
in l937. It also has introduced its 90th Anniversary train set,
which has a GP-9 diesel engine, RailSounds system, operating
headlights, illuminated cab and number plates, and five boxcars
that recall important moments in the line's history.
   - For its own piece of history, a model of the BL2 diesel, made
by Life-Like Products, pulled six passenger cars without stopping
for more than 36 days straight last summer to break the record for
continuous running by a model train and give itself berth in the
``Guinness Book of Records.'' The diesel, modeled after the l950s
Western Maryland vintage engine, is featured in the Proto 2000
Series for serious hobbyists. The company also has sets for other
levels of hobbyists, including its Burlington Bullet and Little Joe
lines.
   - Nostalgia can be combined with high tech with train sets from
Marklin that can be operated either through a personal computer or
through a central control unit of the set. Trains, signals,
switches and other accessories are run digitally.
   - If you're a really older child - say above 25 - you can take
your train on the train in an attache case. Marklin has what it
calls the world's smallest train in a briefcase with a Z-gauge
layout, track, buildings, scenery and controls. Three freight cars
and a locomotive are powered by battery or transformer.
   - Perhaps the train enthusiast will be intrigued by a 1903 model
Renard Road Train, among the antique and collectible toys from
England listed in the Mint &amp; Boxed catalog at 32,000 pounds
sterling, or about $63,000. Less pricey versions of trains, cars,
trucks, boats and other miniatures - including the Matchbox, Corgi
and Dinky lines - are available at M&amp;B's new gallery in New York.
   BRAINFOOD.
   - Tiny scholars learning their numbers and the alphabet get help
from the latest model of the See 'N Say talking toy from Mattel.
This version of the 25-year-old toy has a new pull-lever that
replaces the string mechanism of earlier toys. Jim Henson's Muppets
and Mickey Mouse characters are new features, with Kermit Counts,
to help preschoolers learn to count to ten, and Mickey's ABCs, to
help them learn the alphabet.
   - The Super Speak &amp; Math from Texas Instruments is a talking
calculator in a brightly colored case designed to appeal to
children learning numbers.
   - Children can get into things scientific with Capsela, the
motorized science discovery system from Sanyei. They can learn
principles of mechanics and physics through a series of toys that
feature moving gears housed in clear capsules. The sets have
interlocking, interchangeable parts that can be assembled to create
all kinds of geared or motorized gadgets, include a vacuum cleaner,
a submarine, a hydrojet or racing car. One set, the Capsela 2000
Computer Control System, enables the youngster to build robots
which have a range of over 200 feet. The set has a computer memory
that can store up to 94 commands and operates 17 functions, all
powered by batteries.
   - Geographic literacy is the aim of GeoSafari from Educational
Insights. This electronic quiz game can be used with a variety of
GeoPacks of maps and facts to help youngsters learn about geography
around the world. One new pack, ``Make Your Own,'' lets users make
up a map quiz of their local town, school or state.
   WHATCHITS. From the jocular or innovative giver.
   - What are those strange hairy-looking things? They're Koosh
Kins from OddzOn Products, and they're a family of rubbery
personalities with porcupine hairdos, animated faces and moveable
arms that can grab onto things - maybe even this newspaper.
Theoretically, they are for children, but an adult may not refuse a
gift of Boingo, T.K., Slats, GeeGee, Scopes or Grinby.
   - Speaking of rubbery things, what about a nice big bowl of Guk?
Another almost indescribable product, this potion is something you
get in and grub with. It's mixed with water, feels rubbery or hard
in turn, messes up your fingernails and may even be fun. It's from
Chieftain Products.
   - The Z Ball has bounced its way up from Down Under into the
U.S. market. This Aussie invention, from Fundex, defies the usual
logic of balls, having six sides and protruberances that cause it
to pop, bounce, leap and richochet in unpredictable ways. The
company says it's being used by sports enthusiasts to sharpen
eye-hand coordination; the California Angels and the Boston Red Sox
used the ball during spring training last season.
