<HL> Letters to the Editor:
Peers Looking
For You, Kid</HL>
<DD> 12/15/86</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
   In the Dec. 4 page-one article on the 21 Club in New York, I was interested in the remarks about Humphrey Bogart. 
I attended Trinity School on 91st Street at the same time as Bogart. 
I also was a frequent customer at 21 which, by the way, was not called a club in the early '30s. 
It does not surprise me that he has a brass plate indicating where he sat, as he was one of the best-known of my generation. 

   Apparently that did not impress the editorial staff of the school paper. 
In a blocked-off section were listed the names of alumni of whom the undergraduate editors had heard nothing. 

   The names were listed alphabetically so Bogart's name was near the top. 
Readers were requested to inform the editor if they had heard anything about the people on the list. 

   To quote Charles Churchill, "Fame is but an empty name." 

   C.K. Wildman
   Indialantic, Fla.
</TEXT>
